ce:section.ce:para:
Since carbon dots have been considered for use as biocompatible nanomaterials, we next evaluated the potential of our dots in such applications by performing a cytotoxicity test using MTT assay. MDA-MB-213, a human breast cancer cell, and MDCK, a normal cell line, were used to test the cytotoxicity of the dots. Both types of cell were exposed to carbon dots at different concentrations for 24 h. Our dots showed excellent biocompatibility, with cell viability of over 90% at a carbon dot concentration of 1 g L−1 (Fig. 9
                        ). This matched a report by Dinc et al. using carbon dots from dairy products and similar types of tested cells (Table 1
                        ), suggesting that the carbon dots developed in this work are potential candidates for use in biomedical applications such as cell imaging, biosensors, and drug delivery systems.
